# gitleaks false-positive baseline.
#
# gitleaks ignores findings by FINGERPRINT (not by pattern). A fingerprint looks like:
#   <commit-sha>:<file-path>:<rule-id>:<line-number>
# It is printed in gitleaks' report/output for each finding.
#
# When a confirmed false positive appears (e.g. a test fixture or example value), paste
# its fingerprint on its own line below to suppress it.
# Do NOT suppress a real secret - rotate it, then purge it from history instead.
#
# Example (commented out):
# 0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d:tests/fixtures/sample.env:generic-api-key:12
#
# 2026-07-17: two confirmed false positives from the curl-auth-user rule in the OpenCode
# cross-user security-verification docs. Those docs show an example authenticated request
# to a loopback test server using a documented THROWAWAY credential (a disposable user and
# password created only for the local auth test), which is not a real secret. (This very
# comment deliberately avoids reproducing that literal request line, since doing so would
# itself trip the rule in this file.) The files were later relocated under
# .agents/prompts/reusable/, but the original commit 1efe57d still carries the finding.
